<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911004-0105</DOCNO><DOCID>911004-0105.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Auditor Repeats   Concerns Involving   McDonnell's Finances</HL><DATE>10/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   MD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><RE>MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A top Pentagon auditor repeated concernsthat McDonnell Douglas Corp. may be unable &quot;to raisesufficient cash to maintain ongoing operations,&quot; but thecompany reiterated that its financial situation has greatlyimproved.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,McDonnell Douglas shares closed at $60.875, off $1.875.</LP><TEXT>   William H. Reed, director of the Defense Contract AuditAgency, told the House subcommittee on oversight andinvestigations that McDonnell Douglas's continuing operations&quot;are threatened.&quot;   But a spokesman for the St. Louis-based defensecontractor, which has acknowledged having been severelysqueezed for cash earlier this year, said Mr. Reed'stestimony was based on &quot;old stuff, faulty analysis,unrealistic models -- and not on actual performance to date.&quot;   He said that McDonnell Douglas's debt level is on the waydown, and the company in July registered its best quarterlyearnings performance in more than two years. &quot;Our cashposition continues to improve every day,&quot; the spokesman said.   Still, while acknowledging there has been some improvementin McDonnell Douglas's outlook, Mr. Reed expressed worriesabout a number of projects that have long been viewed asareas of potentially serious cost overruns, including theC-17 cargo jet and Apache helicopter. The panel's chairman,John Dingell (D., Mich.), accused McDonnell Douglas of &quot;plainold-fashioned mismanagement.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>